Date: 5 Dec 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Xinhua News Service, 5 Dec 2000 [edited
<http://202.84.17.11/english/htm/20001204/250050.htm>

Sweden, Norway Act to Prevent BSE Contamination
------------------------------------------------
STOCKHOLM, -- Fearful the brain-wasting bovine spongiform encephalopathy
(BSE) or mad cow disease would spread from the European Union (EU)
countries to their lands, the governments of Sweden and Norway have
announced new steps to prevent contamination with the disease.
According to a new release from the Swedish Administrative Bureau of
Agriculture on Sunday, Sweden's latest preventive measures are to ban, from
1 Jan 2001, the meat and bone meal (MBM) from being mixed into cattle feed.
To make sure cattle feed will be absolutely free of the MBM, made of
carcasses and entrails of animals thought to cause BSE, the bureau ordered
the production of cattle feed to be separated from pig and fowl feed.
Currently, only 40 percent of the cattle feed is produced separately from
pig and fowl feed. In Norway, the country's broadcasting station reported
the consumers administrative bureau urged all grocers nationwide to label
beef with detailed information such as the places of production, slaughter
and packaging. The bureau also called on the quarantine authorities to step
up the quarantine of beef products in a bid to prevent contaminated beef
from entering the Norwegian market.
The customs warned the Norwegians not to buy any beef without the
information of production and slaughter places labeled. As of now, no cases
of BSE have been reported in Norway and Sweden.
Recriminations over the safety of beef appeared to be spreading beyond the
borders of the European Union, but the EU members are still brawling over a
6-month EU-wide ban on MBM.
