[3
Date: 6 Dec 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: ITAR/TASS news Agency, 1 Dec 2000 [edited

MOSCOW -- Russia's veterinary service has not yet banned the import of beef
from Poland, according to the Russian Agriculture Ministry. A case of "mad
cow disease", or bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), can be contracted
by humans as vCJD, has recently been registered at a farm in Poland.
International experts together with Polish ones thoroughly study the
veterinary situation in Poland and have not yet come out with any
statements. Meanwhile, Poland decided on 28 Nov 2000 to ban the import of
beef from Belgium, Germany, Netherlands, Denmark and Spain as more cases of
BSE occur there. Poland had earlier banned the import of British, Irish,
Swiss and French beef.
It was stated in the Russian Agriculture Ministry Russia's veterinary
service guarantees that beef imported from countries of the European Union
is safe. There are Russian veterinaries in each of the countries where
Russia buys meat. They thoroughly check every consignment shipped to Russia.
